views with those who were on the front lines of Communist ideological campaigns, Victoria Smolkin argues that to understand the Soviet experiment, we must make sense of Soviet atheism. Smolkin shows how atheism was reimagined as an alternative cosmology with its own set of positive beliefs, practices, and spiritual commitments. Through its engagements with religion, the Soviet leadership realized that removing religion from the "sacred spaces" of Soviet life was not enough. Then, in the final years of the Soviet experiment, Mikhail Gorbachev-in a stunning and unexpected reversal-abandoned atheism and reintroduced religion into Soviet public life.A Sacred Space Is Never Empty explores the meaning of atheism for religious life, for Communist ideology, and for Soviet politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aAtheismzSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aAtheismzSoviet Union. 0aCommunism and religion. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aBolshevik Revolution.  aBolsheviks.  aBureau for the Registration of Acts of Civil Status.  aCathedral of Christ the Savior.  aHundred Days campaign.  aInstitute of Scientific Atheism.  aJoseph Stalin.  aKomsomol.  aMarxism-Leninism.  aMarxism-Leninism.  aMikhail Gorbachev.  aMoscow Planetarium.  aNikita Khrushchev.  aPenza project.  aRussian Orthodox Church.  aRussian Revolution.  aScience and Religion.  aSoviet Communism.  aSoviet Communist Party.  aSoviet Union.  aSoviet atheism.  aSoviet life.  aSoviet secularization.  aSoviet space programs.  aVladimir Lenin.  aZnanie.  aantireligious propaganda.  aatheism.  aatheist propaganda.  aauthority.  abyt.  aclass morality.  acosmonauts.  acreative intelligentsia.  ade-Stalinization.  aemotions.  afamilies.  alectures.  amarriage rites. 